Same scene as yesterday.

About 8 feet long. Multiple whitish spots on head. Maybe a Salmon Shark instead of a Great White Shark, but those are the two most likely species to be found here, with this fin profile. We were able to eliminate any other likely species to be found here like Blue Shark, Thresher, Basking, and Mako.

About 6-8'. Stayed on the surface for at least 10 minutes, swimming slowly, unconcerned by boat. Had white marks on head area (see other photos), could also be scarring.Thinking maybe basking shark from relaxed behavior, but dorsal looks more swept back (salmon or great white-ish).
8/23 Update: Based on raging debate on Blue Ocean's Facebook page, now convinced it is a great white shark. Apparently this female was injured some time ago and has stayed in this general area.
One of the several young sharks reported cruising not far offshore the coast of Santa Cruz.

Monterey Bay, CA
6/25/2016

10 Foot male White shark stranded off Pleasure Point in Santa Cruz, CA yesterday. The white shark appeared to be sick and stranded. Despite team effort to release it back into the water; it continuously showed up back at the shore break.
The shark did not recover. Arranging follow up recovery and formal lab necropsy, hopefully at local UCSC lab or CDFW or NOAA facility to determine causes. Speculations are that this shark, a sub adult male white shark has stranded due to a Carnobacteroum Infection documented to be killing related species of mako sharks, salmon sharks and thresher sharks (Lamnid/Lamniforms sharks)

For at least the past three years, each summer the area around the ruin of the S.S. Palo Alto becomes a nursery ground for juvenile and subadult White Sharks. Today, at the conclusion of a whale watching trip, we stopped by the area, and saw at least twelve sharks, ranging in size from 5 feet to 14 feet.

For at least the past three years, each summer the area around the ruin of the S.S. Palo Alto becomes a nursery ground for juvenile and subadult White Sharks.  Today, at the conclusion of a whale watching trip, we stopped by the area, and saw at least twelve sharks, ranging in size from 5 feet to 14 feet.
10'-12' long, from the Cement Ship population.  IDed by the captain of the SC Whale Watch vessel.

I called them White Sharks for the following reasons:
1) I got clearer looks at them through my binoculars than I was able to get with the camera, and what I saw was consistent with the White Shark sightings I've had in the same area from whale-watching vessels.
2) Sub-adult and Juvenile White Sharks have been seen consistently in the vicinity of the cement ship between New Brighton SB and Seacliff SB for at least a month this year, and have appeared there in fairly high numbers at this time of year for the past three years, such that it is sometimes possible to see multiple sharks in a short amount of time.
3) I saw at least three individuals in the span of an hour, all in the same general area (roughly a quarter of a mile of coastline.) From what I've been able to gather, the juvenile and sub-adult white sharks are the most likely species to be seen those kind of numbers in that area right now, esp. from shore. 

I admit this is all very circumstantial, but based on the accounts of (http://www.mercurynews.com/2017/06/12/sea-hunt-spending-a-day-searching-for-monsters/), and recent experience I've had with, White Sharks on this stretch of coast this time of year, I'd be very surprised to learn these are not the White Sharks that have been reported from this area.
For the fourth year in a row, juvenile white sharks are congregating between New Brighton Beach and the Cement Ship at Seacliff Beach.  We saw at least four, all 5-9 feet long.

This is the White Shark that caused the advisory at New Brighton State Beach yesterday, when it started cruising around fairly close to shore.  It's one of the group of juvenile and sub-adult sharks that have been hanging around between New Brighton and Seacliff State Beaches for the past three years, arriving about mid-May, and departing around mid-July.

The nursery of Great Whites continues between New Brighton and Seacliff State Beaches.  Today we saw two or three juvenile sharks.  A larger, 8-10 foot shark has been sighted there recently, as well.   (@rjadams55 ...they're baack.)

One of four or five sharks all within a short stretch of New Brighton.  This was the largest, likely 7-8 feet, so far as I can tell.  Although I recognize that it is not possible to make a definitive ID based on these photos, I believe, based on the number of sharks, their behavior, and my past experience in this location, that these were consistent with the well-known population of juvenile and sub-adult white sharks that have been visiting this area of New Brighton/Seacliff SB for the past few summers.
